I just downgraded Pytroch to 1.4.0 and this error has gone. Looks like this problem only affects newer version.

And now I face another strange behavior: ONNX returns all "nan" as prediction on both optimized and raw models. And this new problem appears only when I'm using CUDAExecutionProvider. With CPUExecutionProvider model returns reasonable numbers.
@spandantiwari can you take a look at the PyTorch issue in the newer version? Can you share the converted onnx model you see the error with?

@faxu Here are my models: [raw](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1krber8QWZX_6VTmyhtbiM2ftkTtPYk9D), [gpu optimized](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1-605zZ38f1YgAz9Erxf_wasQNAsDSB_a).

UPD: the problem only reproduces with pytorch==1.5.0, onnxruntime==1.2.0, onnxruntime-gpu==1.2.0
Newer onnxruntime==1.3.0, onnxruntime-gpu==1.3.0 fixed it.

And about nans. I have multiple CUDA installations on my machine. Maybe ONNX Runtime uses the wrong one therefore producing nans? I have cudatoolkit==10.1.243 installed in my conda environment.

UPD: I just  completely removed all CUDA installations and installed CUDA 10.1. NaNs problem is still here.

issue.title: Make softmax component in the CUDA Attention kernel handle cases where mask is 0 any sample in the input

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: There is a softmax component in the CUDA Attention kernel which could introduce numerical instability resulting in NaNs for certain inputs. This change makes it numerically stable.  

**Motivation and Context**
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3977

body:
@SantaDiver, 

I noticed that your model has switched the input naming of attention_mask and token_type_ids, so token_type_ids (all zeros) are used as attention mask. Then the tensor became all zeros (since mask are all zero), that causes NaNs in softmax (Hari has a fix for this). 

You can follow our benchmkark script (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/benchmark.py) to export bert model to ONNX.

Transformers has fixed a similar issue 3 days ago in onnx export: https://github.com/huggingface/transformers/blob/master/src/transformers/convert_graph_to_onnx.py
You can have a try as well.

The epsilon attribute of SkipLayerNormalization is added in onnxruntime 1.3.0. Note that onnxruntime-tools version is 1.3.0.*, and the optimized model might not be backward compatible with older version (1.2.0).

Also, the NaN issue has been addressed:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/2605faef88714b9e9d5ad0eac7f17c387db4cc1c/onnxruntime/contrib_ops/cuda/bert/attention_impl.cu#L158

Close this issue now. Feel free to reopen it if the issue exists in correctly export model.
